Comment: Probably from *_talun₁_ ‘fallow land’ by reduction of an earlier construction *_manuk talun_ ‘jungle fowl’, or the like.
Also _cf_. [Fijian](LanguageTable#cldf:266) _dē ni laŋi_ ‘light scudding clouds’, from the [PMP](LanguageTable#cldf:PMP) doublet *_taqay nu haŋin_.
Also [Maranao](LanguageTable#cldf:331) _tao a mata_ ‘pupil of the eye’.

Also [Kei](LanguageTable#cldf:298) _umat_, [Kairiru](LanguageTable#cldf:667) _ramat_, [Wogeo](LanguageTable#cldf:19063) _ramata_, [Molima](LanguageTable#cldf:18975) _tomotau_, [Proto-Micronesian](LanguageTable#cldf:19079) *_aramata_ ‘person, human being’.  [Dempwolff (1938)](Source#cldf:dempwolff193438) posited *_tau-mataq_ ‘(unripe = not yet dead) living person’, citing an earlier publication by Adriani for the interpretation that the second morphological element in this word is identical to [PAn](LanguageTable#cldf:PAN) *_ma-qetaq_ ‘raw, unripe, green (fruit), uncooked’.  However, no known reflex of this form preserves final consonants, leaving this interpretation uncertain.  Whatever this added element was, it contributed nothing discernible to the semantics of the base, as both [Sangir](LanguageTable#cldf:402) and [Proto-Oceanic](LanguageTable#cldf:19082) have reflexes of [PAn](LanguageTable#cldf:PAN) *_Cau_ next to the longer form with no difference of meaning.
Also [Hawaiian](LanguageTable#cldf:620) _kōhi_ ‘to break off neatly, as taro corm from the stalk; to split, as breadfruit’.

Also [Toba Batak](LanguageTable#cldf:427) _daon_ ‘leaf, medicine’, [Arosi](LanguageTable#cldf:485) _rawa_ Also [Toba Batak](LanguageTable#cldf:427) _daon_ ‘leaf, medicine’, [Arosi](LanguageTable#cldf:485) _rawa_ ‘leaf’.  The secondary meaning ‘head hair’ is widespread in the languages of eastern Indonesia and the Pacific, and looks very much like a Papuan contact feature.  Since this apparent innovation is found as far east as Polynesia it probably was acquired by or before Proto-Oceanic times, and then transmitted like any other feature of the language as Austronesian speakers spread eastward beyond the reach of Papuan contact.  The fact that it also appears in Sama-Bajaw languages, but nowhere else in western Indonesia or the Philippines, lends strength to the hypothesis that it is due to Papuan contact, since the Sama-Bajaw almost certainly were involved in the spice trade that linked the Moluccas of eastern Indonesia with various ports in western Indonesia and the southern Philippines, and so would have had many opportunities for contact with Papuan-speaking groups.


In addition, polymorphemic reflexes in [Bikol](LanguageTable#cldf:244), [Iban](LanguageTable#cldf:276), [Malay](LanguageTable#cldf:326), and [Gitua](LanguageTable#cldf:270) suggest that *_dahun_ figured in the name for the whip snake, a small, green poisonous species that presumably is well camouflaged in foliage, and hence extremely dangerous.  Although a specific term cannot be reconstructed on the basis of known evidence, this may have been [PMP](LanguageTable#cldf:PMP) *_hulaR dahun_.  The names of various birds ([Iban](LanguageTable#cldf:276), [Malay](LanguageTable#cldf:326), [Sundanese](LanguageTable#cldf:418), Bolaang Mongondow) fish ([Malay](LanguageTable#cldf:326), [Sangir](LanguageTable#cldf:402), [Chamorro](LanguageTable#cldf:573), [Manggarai](LanguageTable#cldf:816), [Fijian](LanguageTable#cldf:266), Kapingamarangi), and insects ([Tombonuwo](LanguageTable#cldf:19188), [Malay](LanguageTable#cldf:326)) that incorporate a reflex of [PMP](LanguageTable#cldf:PMP) *_dahun_ may be products of convergence, or retentions of terms for which the surviving evidence is too fragmentary for reconstruction, and the common element in expression such as [Malagasy](LanguageTable#cldf:18432) _daun pintu_ ‘body of door’, [Manggarai](LanguageTable#cldf:816) _sau? para_, [Asilulu](LanguageTable#cldf:18016) _matanulu lau_ ‘door’ probably is the result of historically secondary changes.
Possibly also [Buginese](LanguageTable#cldf:239) _mad-dauŋ_ ‘to flutter in the breeze, as a flag or pennant’.

The agreement between [Malay](LanguageTable#cldf:326) _makan sa-daun_ ‘eat from the same plate’ and [Fijian](LanguageTable#cldf:266) _drau-drau_ ‘the leaves on which food is served up’ are a reminder that in the Austronesian world traditional ‘tables’ (at least for feasts) probably were banana leaves laid out on the ground on which the food was placed.
Also [Balinese](LanguageTable#cldf:235) _don kupiŋ_ ‘the tip of the ear’, [Manggarai](LanguageTable#cldf:816) _sauŋ tilu_ ‘shell of the ear’.
Also [Kambera](LanguageTable#cldf:678) _dàdaluŋu_ ‘stay by a fire; bring into contact with a fire, set on fire’.
¹Li (1978) vacillates between using the terms ‘case marker’ and ‘construction marker’.

Also [Tagalog](LanguageTable#cldf:423) _duryan_, [Mapun](LanguageTable#cldf:19176) _duyan_, [Binukid](LanguageTable#cldf:19012), [Manobo (Western Bukidnon)](LanguageTable#cldf:819), [Mansaka](LanguageTable#cldf:825) _dolyan_ ‘the durian tree and fruit, _Durio zibethinus_ Murr.’, [Maranao](LanguageTable#cldf:331) _dorian_ ‘durian tree: _Durio zibethinus_ Murr.’, _dorian a amoʔ_ ‘soursop: _Annona muricata muricata_ L.’, [Tiruray](LanguageTable#cldf:433) _duriyan_, [Tausug](LanguageTable#cldf:18831) _dūyan_, [Yakan](LanguageTable#cldf:1129) _duwiʔan_, [Javanese](LanguageTable#cldf:285) _durèn_, [Balinese](LanguageTable#cldf:235) _duryan_ ~ _durén_, [Sasak](LanguageTable#cldf:404) _durian_ ~ _durén_, [Balaesang](LanguageTable#cldf:19201), [Totoli](LanguageTable#cldf:1084) _durian_, [Dampelas](LanguageTable#cldf:18954) _duhian_, Taje _ruriaŋ_, [Uma](LanguageTable#cldf:19170) _duri_, [Bare'e](LanguageTable#cldf:236) _oria_, [Wolio](LanguageTable#cldf:1124) _duria_, [Tae'](LanguageTable#cldf:18947) _durian_, [Mandar](LanguageTable#cldf:813), [Buginese](LanguageTable#cldf:239), [Makassarese](LanguageTable#cldf:325) _duriaŋ_ ‘durian tree and fruit’.  



From *_duRi_ ‘thorn’ + _-an_.  [Malay](LanguageTable#cldf:326) _durian_ does not show the expected neutralization of prepenultimate vowels as schwa, possibly because this form was still perceived as bimorphemic.  A number of reflexes in the Philippines and Sulawesi are best explained as [Malay](LanguageTable#cldf:326) loans, but this is impossible for Tau’t Batu (Palawan) _dugyan_, and for such obviously native forms as [Berawan (Long Terawan)](LanguageTable#cldf:19191) _kəjin_, and [Kiput](LanguageTable#cldf:18958) _ləcin_, which show highly distinctive phonological developments.  The distributional evidence for this form suggests that the durian was first encountered by AN speakers in Palawan or Borneo and at a later date was carried south and east by Malay traders.
Also [Bintulu](LanguageTable#cldf:242) _kəm-ina_ ‘aunt; mother’s sister, father’s sister’.

Also [Erai](LanguageTable#cldf:263) _méha_ ‘only, alone’, and the morphological parallel in [Kelabit](LanguageTable#cldf:299) _edheh_ ‘one’, _midheh_ ‘once’.  [Tagalog](LanguageTable#cldf:423) _mag-isá_ ‘be alone, do something alone’ suggests that [Hanunóo](LanguageTable#cldf:273) _maysá_ may reflect *_maR-isa_.  [Mills (1975:712)](Source#cldf:mills1975) posits [Proto-South Sulawesi](LanguageTable#cldf:19092) *_(ma-)isa_ ‘one’.

Also [Fijian](LanguageTable#cldf:266) _keda_ ‘we (plural incl.)’.  Forms that appear to reflect *_i-kita_ have simply incorporated the closely bound personal case marker for first and second person reference (less commonly, some languages have extended a reflex of *_si_, the bound personal case marker for third person reference to the base *_ita_ or *_kita_. Since this was not an affix in [PAn](LanguageTable#cldf:PAN) it is not treated as part of morphology here.  It has long been known that first person plural pronouns have two distinct shapes (*_ami_/_kami_, *_ita_/_kita_), but both the morphology and the semantics that distinguish these pairs have remained elusive.  Some languages have _k_-initial forms for all non-third person forms, as with [Amis](LanguageTable#cldf:227) _kako_ ‘I’, _kiso_ ‘you’, _ciŋra_ ~ _ciira_ ‘s/he’, _kita_ ‘we (incl.)’, _kami_ ‘we (excl.)’, _kamo_ ‘you (pl.)’, _caŋra_ ~ _caira_ ‘they’.  Others, as [Karo Batak](LanguageTable#cldf:18314) or [Toba Batak](LanguageTable#cldf:427), contrast _k_-initial forms which function as more formal expressions of plural reference, or as polite 2nd sg. reference, with vowel-initial forms which function as familiar or intimate expressions of plural reference, and are not used at all in singular reference.  There is little evidence that the forms *_kita_ and *_kami_ are bimorphemic, and the best option based on present evidence appears to be that vowel-initial and _*k_-initial forms were variants that conveyed distinctions of formality in [PAn](LanguageTable#cldf:PAN). Reflexes that are ambiguous for *_ita_ or *_kita_ have been assigned to the latter, since it is somewhat more common than the former.

¹ [Ross (2006:529)](bib-Ross) gives [Saisiyat](LanguageTable#cldf:400) _ka_ as marking both NOM and ACC, but according to [Li (1978:600)](Source#cldf:li1978), and [Zeitoun (to appear)](bib-Zeitoun) it marks only the ACC.
In contemporary standard [Bikol](LanguageTable#cldf:244) _makakán_ evidently is _ma-kakán_, but comparative evidence shows that this almost certainly is a reanalysis of earlier _maka-kan_.
Also [Gaddang](LanguageTable#cldf:268), [Yogad](LanguageTable#cldf:19274) _me-ŋŋan_, [Lampung](LanguageTable#cldf:722) _me-ŋa_n ‘to eat’.
Also [Kavalan](LanguageTable#cldf:293) _ti-qan_ ‘to eat with (instrumental focus)’.

Also [Sangir](LanguageTable#cldf:402) _ka-kanəŋ-aŋ_ ‘eating place, eating trough’.  Presumably with *_ka- -an_ ‘formative for abstract nouns’, although most reflexes of *_ka-kaen-an_ appear to be concrete.
[Roviana](LanguageTable#cldf:396) _g<in>ani_ is assumed to be a reformation made by infixing the reflex of [POc](LanguageTable#cldf:POC) *_kani_.

Also [Kenyah (Long Anap)](LanguageTable#cldf:317) _uman_ ‘to eat’ (presumably a back-formation from 
_pə-ŋ<um>an_ ‘food (in general), where the base could potentially begin with _k_ or zero.

Also [Gilbertese](LanguageTable#cldf:614) _kaŋ_ ‘to eat, to consume’, [Pohnpeian](LanguageTable#cldf:381), [Mokilese](LanguageTable#cldf:342), [Kosraean](LanguageTable#cldf:713) _kaŋ_ ‘to eat’, [Woleaian](LanguageTable#cldf:443) _gaŋ-i_ ‘eat it’.
[Roviana](LanguageTable#cldf:396) shows unexplained loss of the final consonant.

Comment: Also [Karo Batak](LanguageTable#cldf:18314) _ŋ-kutu-i_ ‘delouse someone’, [Toba Batak](LanguageTable#cldf:427) _maŋ-hutu-i_ ‘delouse someone’.
Possibly a reduction of earlier _kələ-lawaʔ_ (cp. [Kelabit](LanguageTable#cldf:299) _kələ-lawaʔ_ ~ _kə-lawaʔ_ ‘spider’.

Probably with a variant of the *_qalikali_- prefix found on the names of many ‘creepy-crawly’ creatures that evidently were protected by a taboo against random killing ([Blust 2001](Source#cldf:blust2001)).
This [PMP](LanguageTable#cldf:PMP) construction replaced [PAn](LanguageTable#cldf:PAN) *_ma-lima-N_ ‘fifty’.
Presumably with the same numeral marker that appears as _e_ in other Oceanic languages.

For [Mongondow](LanguageTable#cldf:245) _i-lima_ ‘the fifth’ cp. e.g. [Kadazan Dusun](LanguageTable#cldf:287) _iŋg-onom_, [Malagasy](LanguageTable#cldf:18432) _in-énina_ ‘six times’,[Mongondow](LanguageTable#cldf:245) _iŋg-onon_ ‘the sixth’.  This still poorly understood numeral prefix evidently had different allomorphs before vowel-initial and consonant-initial bases.

In many languages it is difficult to disinguish reflexes of this form from reflexes of [PAn](LanguageTable#cldf:PAN) *_Sika-lima_ ‘the fifth’.  Both *_ka-lima_ and *_maka-lima_ appear to have meant ‘five times’, and it is therefore possible that the data taken to support this shorter word are actually truncated forms of *_maka-lima_.
Possibly _*k<um>a-lima_ ‘become fifth’.

[Onvlee (1984)](Source#cldf:onvlee1984) gives [Kambera](LanguageTable#cldf:678) _njara makalimangu baina_ ‘a stallion with five mares’ (lit. ‘a stallion, five times his mares’, but this appears to be _njara ma-ka-lima-ŋu bai-na_ ).  It is possible that the [PAn](LanguageTable#cldf:PAN) form meaning ‘five times’ was *_maka-lima-N_.
Although the prefix in this form clearly was _*maŋ-_, it may have had an allomorph [_maŋa_] before bases that began with a liquid consonant.

This form is puzzling, as it is clearly derived from *_lima_ ‘five’, but *_qa-_ is not a known affix.  A number of other languages reflect *_lima_ as both ‘five’ and ‘hand’, in the latter meaning presumably by reduction of the longer form.  In other cases the two senses are distinguished by stress, as in [Bontok](LanguageTable#cldf:246) _limá_ ‘five’ : _líma_ ‘hand and arm’, or [Kankanaey](LanguageTable#cldf:289) _limá_ ‘five’ : _líma_, _ma-limá-an_ ‘manipulated; rickety, as chickens or dogs that are manipulated too much in their youth’.  The latter meaning raises questions about whether seemingly distinct items such as [Cebuano](LanguageTable#cldf:252) _alíma_ ‘take care of someone by administering to his needs’, or [Manobo (Western Bukidnon)](LanguageTable#cldf:819) _elima_ ‘to care for; to look after; to provide for, as children, plants, garden, animals, etc.’ might also be related (cf. English ‘to handle someone’s affairs’).
The reconstruction of this pattern for multiples of ten in [PAn](LanguageTable#cldf:PAN) was first demonstrated by [Zeitoun, Teng and Ferrell (2010)](bib-Zeitoun).

[Puyuma](LanguageTable#cldf:386) ([Tsuchida 1980](Source#cldf:tsuchida1980)) also has a pattern _paR-X-n_ for bases ending in a vowel, and _paR-X-en_ for bases ending in a consonant, meaning ‘to do X times’.  However, for this affixational pattern the innovative form _luwaT_ ‘five’ is used, yielding _paR-luwaT_ ‘to do five times’.  While this form cannot be directly compared with those in Philippine languages, it does suggest that if a reflex of *_lima_ had been retained in this type of construction the result would have been **_paR-lima-n_, and the reconstruction given here would then be upgraded to [PAn](LanguageTable#cldf:PAN).
Thanks to Keane Domenguez for drawing my attention to the meaning ‘small-meshed’ in association with [Hawaiian](LanguageTable#cldf:620) _makaliʔi_.

The agreement of [Cebuano](LanguageTable#cldf:252) and [Buginese](LanguageTable#cldf:239) in containing a reduplicated for of [PMP](LanguageTable#cldf:PMP) *_tau_ ‘person, human being’ may indicate an alternative construction *_tau tau nu mata_, in which the reduplication of *_tau_ marks simulative, since the ‘person’ in the eye is an image, not a literal being.

This complex term clearly referred to the direction of the wind (in sailing).  In [Proto-Polynesian](LanguageTable#cldf:19084) the original morpheme boundary was lost and the adjacent low vowels fused into a single short vowel.  The unanalyzable morpheme _mataŋi_ then came to refer to the wind in general (although the reflex in [Rennellese](LanguageTable#cldf:390) retains the original sense in addition to the general sense of ‘wind’).  [Niue](LanguageTable#cldf:362) _mata mataŋi_ appears to be an attempt to restore the original sense of directionality by repeating _mata_ ‘eye’ as an independent morpheme, since the original morphology has been lost, and with it the specifying property of *_mata_.

Also [Cebuano](LanguageTable#cldf:252) _matá sa báliŋ_ ‘mesh of a net’, [Iban](LanguageTable#cldf:276) _mata jala_ ‘meshes added when making a cast-net to increase diameter and produce cone shape’, [Sangir](LanguageTable#cldf:402) _mata-n soma_ ‘mesh of a net’.  The reconstruction with *_puket_ is supported by comparative evidence, but *_mata_ undoubtedly was used with reference to the mesh of nets in general, an association that is also found in languages that belong to other genetic groupings, as Japanese (_ami no me_; net GEN eye), and Hebrew (_ayin ha rέʃεt_).  In some cases it is unclear whether the reference is to the holes in the net or to the knots that give it structure.
Also [Simalur](LanguageTable#cldf:415) _mata-n totuʔ_ ‘nipple of the breast’.
Also [Mailu](LanguageTable#cldf:774) _mata-mata_ ‘to appear’, presumably a loan from a still unidentified Austronesian source.
Also [Gitua](LanguageTable#cldf:270) _manum_ ‘bird’.

Also [Isneg](LanguageTable#cldf:647) _anúʔ_ ‘the barnyard fowl or chicken’, _an-anúʔ_ ‘a general name for birds’, [Malay](LanguageTable#cldf:326) _manok-manok_ ‘a tree: sp. unident.’, [Karo Batak](LanguageTable#cldf:18314) _anuk-anuk_ ‘bird (generic)’, ['Āre'āre](LanguageTable#cldf:18004) _mānu_ ‘bird, insect, said of anything that flies’.  This semantic history of this form is discussed in [Blust (2002)](Source#cldf:blust2002), where it is noted that [PMP](LanguageTable#cldf:PMP) *_manuk_ clearly meant ‘chicken’, and the generic term for ‘bird’ was formed from it by reduplication as *_manuk-manuk_, or possibly *_manu-manuk_.  In [Proto-Oceanic](LanguageTable#cldf:19082), however, *_manuk_ had already shifted its sense from ‘chicken’ to ‘bird’, and the reduplicated form came to mean ‘insect, small flying creatures other than birds’.  Whether the [Basai](LanguageTable#cldf:19171) and [Trobiawan](LanguageTable#cldf:19209) terms in Taiwan are native or loans from a Philippine source during the Spanish occupation of northern Taiwan from 1626 to 1642 remains an open question, although the fact that they mean ‘bird’, while nearly all unreduplicated forms in Philippine languages mean ‘chicken’ supports the view that they are native, and that *_manuk_ can thus be assigned to [PAn](LanguageTable#cldf:PAN), presumably in the meaning ‘chicken’ (next to *_qayam_ ‘bird’).
Given its modern implications this form probably is a product of independent development.

An affixed form *_manuk-en_ can be posited for [Proto-Philippines](LanguageTable#cldf:19083), but it is unclear what this word meant.  Reflexes in [Ilokano](LanguageTable#cldf:279), [Tagalog](LanguageTable#cldf:423)  and [Tausug](LanguageTable#cldf:18831)  evidently derive from the sponsorship and betting that typically take place in cockfighting, but the antiquity of cockfighting in the Austronesian world remains uncertain ([Blust 2002:96-98](Source#cldf:blust2002)).  Reflexes in [Casiguran Dumagat](LanguageTable#cldf:569)  and [Ibaloy](LanguageTable#cldf:19182) suggest what is perhaps an older meaning, namely the taking of omens from the flight of birds or examination of the entrails of chickens.  The meaning ‘crosseyed’, which is shared by [Bikol](LanguageTable#cldf:244) and [Maranao](LanguageTable#cldf:331) is distinct from either of these, but is not sufficiently widely attested to attribute to [Proto-Philippines](LanguageTable#cldf:19083).
This word seems to derive ultimately from _*si anu_, although the contracted form may already have existed in [PMP](LanguageTable#cldf:PMP).
[Old Javanese](LanguageTable#cldf:660) _pa-ŋaran_ and [Yamdena](LanguageTable#cldf:1130) _na-f-ŋare_ may reflext *_pa-ŋajan_.
Possibly a product of convergence.

This prefixed form clearly parallels the use of _Ca-_ reduplication in the formation of numerals with human referents, although it is unclear whether all forms that appear to be traceable to *_pa-pija_ have the same history (e.g. [Fordata](LanguageTable#cldf:18184) _fa-fira_ ‘how often?’, or even the [Proto-Bungku-Tolaki](LanguageTable#cldf:19187) form cited above).
[Muna](LanguageTable#cldf:350) _pi-pitu_ may reflect *_pa-pitu_ with vocalic assimilation or leveling of _Ca-_ and _CV-_ reduplication.

Further evidence that the numeral ligature in this expression was *_ŋa_ is seen in [Kelai](LanguageTable#cldf:19768) _tujuh ŋəh puluʔ_ ‘70’, which uses the innovative base _tujuh_ ‘seven’, but preserves the structure of the multiplicative construction.
Possibly a chance resemblance.
Compare [Kadazan Dusun](LanguageTable#cldf:287) _opod_ ‘ten’ : _iŋg-opod_ ‘ten times’, with a different base form, and similar but non-corresponding form of the prefix.
This either an alternative to the much better-attested [PMP](LanguageTable#cldf:PMP) *_mata ni susu_ nipple of the breast, or a convergent development in a small number of languages.
Also [Kapampangan](LanguageTable#cldf:291) _sakló_ ‘to fetch (e.g. water)’.

The expected form in [Old Javanese](LanguageTable#cldf:660) is **_ma-ñakit_.  It is unclear why nasal substitution in this form and in other forms of this base that take a prefix ending with _–N_ violates the general pattern by which /_s_/ is replaced by a palatal nasal.
Also [Malagasy](LanguageTable#cldf:18432) _nala_ ‘a moral defect, a vice’.

Also [Mapun](LanguageTable#cldf:19176) _mag-sāʔ_ ‘make a mistake; to err; to be wrong’, [Yakan](LanguageTable#cldf:1129) _mag-salaʔ_ ‘for something to be wrong; esp. sprained, dislocated (it is used mostly of the body)’, with an affix borrowed from some Greater Central Philippines source.
Also [Karo Batak](LanguageTable#cldf:18314) _ke-salah-en_ ‘guilty’.

Also [Fijian](LanguageTable#cldf:266) _ba-saŋa_ ‘starfish; branchy’.  This word seems clearly to derive from [PMP](LanguageTable#cldf:PMP) *_saŋa_ ‘bifurcation; to branch’, with pluralizing reduplication (the starfish being conceived as a radial sequence of bifurcations).  For similar formations with variant bases, cp. [Sangir](LanguageTable#cldf:402) _peŋaʔ_ ‘spread wide, as the legs of a person’, _pem-peŋaʔ ‘_starfish’, and [Nukuoro](LanguageTable#cldf:363) _maŋa_ ‘a branch’, _manu maŋa-maŋa_ ‘starfish; branchy’.

[Yakan](LanguageTable#cldf:1129) _sabit-an_ ‘web belt (wide and stiff, predominantly green in color; it has a zippered pocket and is usually worn by older men)’ is assumed to be a loan from a Greater Central Philippines language.

The expected form of this word in [Old Javanese](LanguageTable#cldf:660) is **pañiku (with regular nasal substitution of the palatal nasal for /_s_/).  I assume an irregularity in [Old Javanese](LanguageTable#cldf:660), not in [PWMP](LanguageTable#cldf:PWMP).
[Mapun](LanguageTable#cldf:19176) _sipit-un_ ‘to pinch or clamp something between something’ is assumed to be a borrowing from a Greater Central Philippines language.

Comment: Oceanic forms that reflect *_paka-_ presumably are secondary reformations from the earlier form *_pa-susu_.

Also [Nukuoro](LanguageTable#cldf:363) _lahhie_ ‘firewood’.  [Walsh and Biggs (1966)](Source#cldf:walshandbiggs1966) give [Rarotongan](LanguageTable#cldf:388) _vaʔie_ ‘firewood’, but this appears as _vaie_, with unexplained zero reflex for medial *_f_ in their reported source ([Savage 1962](bib-Savage)).  Although the Oceanic forms can be regularly derived from [PMP](LanguageTable#cldf:PMP) *_pa-hapuy-an_, and although [POc](LanguageTable#cldf:POC) preserved *_api_ ‘fire’ it is unlikely that the morphological relationship between *_api_ and *_papian_ was apparent to speakers of [POc](LanguageTable#cldf:POC), which had already undergone such a thorough morphological restructuring that many original morpheme boundaries were completely concealed from the average speaker.  Except for the reported [Maori](LanguageTable#cldf:330) variant _fafia_, all Polynesian reflexes show an irregular fronting of the final vowel, a change that presumably had already occurred in PPn, perhaps giving rise to doublets *_fafie_ and *_fafia_.
[Bimanese](LanguageTable#cldf:241) _ka-dahu_ may reflect *_paka-takut_, and it is possible that the prefixed element in the other forms cited together here actually has disparate sources.

This form of the causative prefix with *_takut_ is clearly in competition with the causative of stative verbs, *_paka-_. It is possible that the [Kelabit](LanguageTable#cldf:299) and [Sasak](LanguageTable#cldf:404) forms given here are historically secondary reformations from *_paka-takut_.

The [Tae'](LanguageTable#cldf:18947) form shows that some of these constructions may have been innovated in the separate histories of the languages in which they are found, since in at least this case the circumfixation of _ka- -an_ took place only after prefixation with _ma-_.

Doublet_Comment: *amiaŋ 'generic for plants with stinging hairs or hairs that cause itchiness'

Comment: Also [Wetan](LanguageTable#cldf:1118) _tienni_ ‘to weave’.

Also [Pazeh](LanguageTable#cldf:375) _tuʔun_ ‘to weave (cloth); to weave (a mat)’, _saa-tuʔun_ ‘weaving instruments in general’, _ta-tuʔun-an_ ‘a weaving machine’, [Tialo](LanguageTable#cldf:1063) _toun_ ‘to weave cloth’.
[Malagasy](LanguageTable#cldf:18432) _tenom-ina_ may be a hypercorrection, since *_-m_ > _-n_, but the alveolar nasal then alternates with its labial source before a suffix.
Also [Palauan](LanguageTable#cldf:372) _dióll_ pregnant.

Also [Paiwan](LanguageTable#cldf:370) _tsudjuq-an_ ‘a finger’, a form that appears to point to [PAn](LanguageTable#cldf:PAN) *_Cuzuq_ rather than *_tuzuq_. With infix *__, parallel to [PAn](LanguageTable#cldf:PAN) *_kuSkuS_ ‘claw, talon, fingernail’.
Also [Tagalog](LanguageTable#cldf:423) _kánan_ ‘right; right-hand side’, apparently a borrowing of [Malay](LanguageTable#cldf:326) _kanan_.
